        {
            "id": "DJN_DN20251225000948:0",
            "title": "Tokyo Consumer Inflation Slows But Remains Above BOJ's Target",
            "description": "<div class=\"body-KX2tCBZq body-pIO_GYwT content-pIO_GYwT\"><div class=\"symbolsContainer-cBh_FN2P logosContainer-cwMMKgmm\" data-no-swipe=\"true\"></div><div><span><p class=\"\"><span>By Megumi Fujikawa</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>TOKYO--Consumer inflation in the Tokyo metropolitan area slowed in December but remained above the Bank of Japan's 2% target, keeping the central bank on track for further monetary tightening.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Consumer prices in Tokyo, excluding fresh food, rose 2.3% year-over-year, easing from November's 2.8% increase, government data showed on Friday.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The reading was lower than the 2.5% increase expected in a poll of economists by data provider Quick.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Tokyo figures are widely viewed as a leading indicator of nationwide inflation trends.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The Japanese central bank last week raised its policy rate by 25 basis points to 0.75%, the highest level in 30 years, reflecting confidence that the nation's wage-price mechanism is functioning smoothly.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>BOJ Gov. Kazuo Ueda has said that real interest rates remain significantly low even after the latest increase, pledging to adjust monetary policy further if economic and price data align with the central bank's projections.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Write to Megumi Fujikawa at megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com</span></p></span></div></div>",
            "link": "https://www.tradingview.com/news/DJN_DN20251225000948:0/",
            "pub_date": "2025-12-26 07:51:00",
            "source": "Dow Jones Newswires",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
